Consider a game where there are n children (numbered 1,2,...,n) in a circle. During the game, repeatedly k children are skipped and one child is removed from the circle. In which order will the children be removed?

Input:
The only input line has two integers n and k.

Output:
Print n integers: the removal order.

Constraints:
1 <= n <= 2*10^5
0 <= k <= 10^9

Strategy:
This problem cannot be solved with a queue like the first one since worst case we always have to remove the whole queue. This one was absolutely out of my league and skillset and it doesn't even seem it belongs here. The solution AI recommended was a Fenwick tree which I didn't wanna get into and the second thing was a special kind of set which allows for O(logn) retrieval by index and also O(logn) deletion and insertion like a normal RBT. It is a special kind of RBT which stays sorted but also allows the index searches. This way we can just put everything in and then just keep an index of the next thing. We do this by starting at 1, doing idx = (idx+k)%set.size(), accessing the number, printing it and erasing it from the set. We repeat this until it's empty.